(21876,'cars','rom','pgmfi-d51','en','Pgmfi D51','blundar modified a dasm he found, D51, to support the A5 instruction as is peculiar on the Oki 8XC154 MCUs.','advanced','blundar modified a dasm he found, D51, to support the A5 instruction as is peculiar on the Oki 8XC154 [MCU](/cars/rom/mcu)s. Blundar made linux binaries. Chris D make windows binaries. Look at the source / read command line parameters for help.\n\n| **Attachment:** | **Modify:** | **Size:** | **Date:** | **Who:** | **Comment:** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/zip.gif) [D51\\\\_w32.zip](D51_w32.zip) | mod | 33119 | 05 Mar 2004 - 19:40 | blundar | VC++ Win32 binary, zipped |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/zip.gif) [D51\\\\_W32\\\\_Source.zip](D51_W32_Source.zip) | mod | 39722 | 05 Mar 2004 - 19:40 | blundar | Source / VC++ project files |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/zip.gif) [d51v3.12-linux.zip](d51v3.12-linux.zip) | mod | 475876 | 05 Mar 2004 - 19:40 | blundar | Linux source/binaries |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/else.gif) [91.ctl](91.ctl) | mod | 85 | 05 Mar 2004 - 19:41 | blundar | Simple control file for 91 PM6 |','cars/rom/pgmfi-d51/pgmfi-d51.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21877,'cars','rom','piggy-back','en','Piggy Back','A Piggy Back controller is a device that \"piggybacks\" on top of the ECU. Piggybacks intercept signals coming from the engine and alter them before they reach the ECU.','beginner','A [Piggy Back](/cars/rom/piggy-back) controller is a device that \"piggybacks\" on top of the [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu). Piggybacks intercept signals coming from the engine and alter them before they reach the [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu). The most commonly abused piggyback controllers are the Apexi SAFC, VAFC, SAFC2 and VAFC2. The Greddy E-Manage is a big badass piggyback controller on steroids. You could think of a lot of the garbage that comes with a JRSC kit as a piggyback, as their relay and crap setup causes bogus sensor values to be passed to the [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu).','cars/rom/piggy-back/piggy-back.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21878,'cars','rom','pj0','en','PJ0','The A20A 8689 Accord/Prelude PJ0 ECU had many revisions in different countries. Some of them will lack an O2 sensor or EGR control.','intermediate','The A20A 86-89 Accord/Prelude PJ0 [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu) had many revisions in different countries. Some of them will lack an O2 sensor or EGR control. However, they all use a vacuum advance distributor.\n\nMost those [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu)s were made by Matsushita. Some of them (86-87?)use an external 128k [ROM](/cars/rom/rom).\n\nThe California Emissions PJ0 were OKI `80C154` based and always use a 128k External [ROM](/cars/rom/rom)\n\n| **Attachment:** | **Modify:** | **Size:** | **Date:** | **Who:** | **Comment:** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PJ0-A03.jpg](PJ0-A03.jpg) | mod | 282684 | 30 Jan 2006 - 06:54 | carotman | Canadian 89 Accord [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu). Made by Matsushita |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PJ0-604-2.JPG](PJ0-604-2.JPG) | mod | 588048 | 30 Jan 2006 - 07:13 | carotman | [EDM](/cars/wiring/edm) A20A4 no EGR and no O2 sensor from an 89 EX-i |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PJ0\\\\_L022.JPG](PJ0_L022.JPG) | mod | 212536 | 08 Feb 2006 - 22:55 | carotman | California Emissions PJ0 [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu). OKI based |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PJ0-666-front.jpg](PJ0-666-front.jpg) | mod | 797657 | 29 Dec 2006 - 20:22 | carotman | [USDM](/cars/sensors/usdm) 86-87 Prelude SI PJ0 [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu) |','cars/rom/pj0/pj0.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21879,'cars','rom','pl2','en','PL2','PL2 : 8?88+ Acura/Rover V6 (C25/C27) Attachment: Modify: Size: Date: Who: Comment: : : : : : :','intermediate','PL2 : 8?-88+ Acura/Rover V6 (`C25`/`C27`)\n\n| **Attachment:** | **Modify:** | **Size:** | **Date:** | **Who:** | **Comment:** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PL2insidebottom.jpg](PL2insidebottom.jpg) | mod | 230714 | 17 Dec 2003 - 22:55 | The Admin | PL2 [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu) scan from Simon Stirley |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PL2insidetop.jpg](PL2insidetop.jpg) | mod | 192631 | 17 Dec 2003 - 22:55 | The Admin | PL2 Scan from Simon Stirley |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PL2mlbottom.jpg](PL2mlbottom.jpg) | mod | 366138 | 17 Dec 2003 - 22:57 | The Admin | PL2 solder side scan from Mark Lamond |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PL2mltop.jpg](PL2mltop.jpg) | mod | 309996 | 17 Dec 2003 - 22:57 | The Admin | PL2 Top side scan from Mark Lamond |','cars/rom/pl2/pl2.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21880,'cars','rom','pm5','en','PM5','PM5 8891 Civic base model/CRX DX (DPFI D15b) There were two distinct styles of this ECU. One features an 83C154 MCU, one features a 66201 MCU.','advanced','PM5 88-91 Civic base model/CRX DX ([DPFI](/cars/sensors/dpfi) D15b) There were two distinct styles of this [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu). One features an `83C154` [MCU](/cars/rom/mcu), one features a 66201 [MCU](/cars/rom/mcu). Presumably 88-89 vs 90-91 ?\n\n- PM5 dx [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu), \"old\" `83C154` style, thanks TJ: \n     ![PM5dxTJ.jpg](PM5dxTJ.jpg)\n\n| **Attachment:** | **Modify:** | **Size:** | **Date:** | **Who:** | **Comment:** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PM5dxTJ.jpg](PM5dxTJ.jpg) | mod | 207404 | 22 Jul 2004 - 16:33 | blundar | PM5 dx [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu), thanks TJ |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [PM5-230.jpg](PM5-230.jpg) | mod | 70958 | 22 Jul 2004 - 16:34 | blundar | closeup of [ROM](/cars/rom/rom) area on 90-91 PM5 |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [pm5-230\\\\_rom.gif](pm5-230_rom.gif) | mod | 343664 | 20 Mar 2005 - 18:32 | 1net | one more 90-91 PM5 ( chips readable) |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [DSC00474.JPG](DSC00474.JPG) | mod | 2382041 | 08 Jul 2005 - 14:52 | 1net | 90-91 PM5 (image is great for comparing P04 & PM5) |','cars/rom/pm5/pm5.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21881,'cars','rom','pm9','en','PM9','Essentially a PM5The PM5 + PM9 are essentially the same ECU. I think one may have been for the 4 speed and one the 5 speed, but I\'m not sure.','advanced','Essentially a [PM5](/cars/rom/pm5)The PM5 + PM9 are essentially the same [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu). I think one may have been for the 4 speed and one the 5 speed, but I\'m not sure. (blundar) The PM9 that I posted was from a 4 speed HF model Civic. You may be correct in your thoughts. (Warrick) The PM5+PM9 used two distinct designs (kinda like the [PG7](/cars/sensors/pg7)) - the 88-89 Use an `83C154` while the 90-91 use a 66201. The 90-91 processor quadrant looks a lot like an [OBD](/cars/wiring/obd)1 [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu).\n\n| **Attachment:** | **Modify:** | **Size:** | **Date:** | **Who:** | **Comment:** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [pm9top.jpg](pm9top.jpg) | mod | 532694 | 25 May 2004 - 17:20 | warrick | PM9 top view |\n| ![](/pgmfi/wiki/assets/icn/bmp.gif) [pm9bottom.jpg](pm9bottom.jpg) | mod | 492973 | 25 May 2004 - 17:22 | warrick | PM9 bottom view |','cars/rom/pm9/pm9.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21882,'cars','rom','pocket-programmer2','en','Pocket Programmer2','The Pocket Programmer 2 lists at $149.95 as of October 9, 2003. It has not fluctuated in price much. It supports a wide variety of chips, has decent software for windows and dos.','intermediate','The [Pocket Programmer 2](https://www.xtronics.com/memory/EPROM.htm) lists at $149.95 as of October 9, 2003. It has not fluctuated in price much. It supports a wide variety of chips, has decent software for windows and dos. It can burn [MCU](/cars/rom/mcu)s and all sorts of weird chips through a variety of add-on adapters. This is a very common [Rom Burner](/cars/ecu/rom-burner) as it was packaged with [Hondata](http://www.hondata.com). IMHO, the pocket programmer 2 isn\'t a bad deal, particularly for someone seeking a polished product. Xtronics technical support is pretty decent, they keep the software up to date but I\'ve seen many of these programmers be very, very, very peculiar. I never successfully burned a [ROM](/cars/rom/rom) with my old thinkpad T20, but it worked fine with my current thinkpad T21. Not a bad burner for the price, but after using the [Super Pro Z](/cars/diagnostics/super-pro-z) I\'d never buy one again. -Dave','cars/rom/pocket-programmer2/pocket-programmer2.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21883,'cars','rom','prelude-accord','en','Prelude Accord','OK, here is what I know about these ECUs. The PT6A51 I have here has a 66911 MCU and uses an external 256k PROM.','beginner','OK, here is what I know about these [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu)s. The PT6-A51 I have here has a 66911 [MCU](/cars/rom/mcu) and uses an external 256k PROM. I got an [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu) out of a 1994 Prelude SI with a 1.6 [DOHC](/cars/sensors/dohc) and it has a PK3-A00 and it also has the OKI 66911 [MCU](/cars/rom/mcu) and external 256Kbit PROM, plus has the `74HC373` -- sloopy - 16 May 2005','cars/rom/prelude-accord/prelude-accord.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21884,'cars','rom','pressure-atmosphere','en','Pressure Atmosphere','the atmospheric pressure sensor, also called \'\'barometric pressure\'\' or \'\'PA\'\' sensor measures a much narrower range of pressure centered(??) around atmospheric pressure.','beginner','the atmospheric pressure sensor, also called \'\'barometric pressure\'\' or ***\'\'PA\'\'*** sensor measures a much narrower range of pressure centered(??) around atmospheric pressure. It is used to adjust the fuel mixture to account for differences in air density due to altitude or weather. inside the [ECU](/cars/ecu/ecu)','cars/rom/pressure-atmosphere/pressure-atmosphere.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
(21885,'cars','rom','recent-changes','en','Recent Changes','Here\'s a list of recently changed pages on this wiki. (See Recent Edits for all recent minor edits and changes).','beginner','Here\'s a list of recently changed pages on this wiki. (See [Recent Edits](/cars/rom/recent-edits) for all recent minor edits and changes).\n\n---\n\nRecent Changes days||=7 daylist=1,3,7,30,90, 0 ?>','cars/rom/recent-changes/recent-changes.md','2026-06-15 22:15:12',0),
